WEBVTT

00:05.880 --> 00:08.842
I shot the sheriff

00:08.883 --> 00:12.762
But I didn't shoot no deputy

00:12.804 --> 00:15.473
Oh, no, oh

00:15.515 --> 00:19.978
I shot the sheriff

00:20.020 --> 00:21.896
But I didn't shoot no deputy

00:23.732 --> 00:26.818
"Fords bring dancing
      back to the White House."

00:26.860 --> 00:30.655
Well, what can I say?
            I'm a dancer.

00:30.697 --> 00:32.699
-Your mother was fantastic.

00:32.741 --> 00:36.327
Your father and I
        are a very good team.

00:36.369 --> 00:39.664
Now you just have to deal
   with Nixon, Dad. No big whoop.

00:39.706 --> 00:42.000
Just sending
    a former president to prison.

00:42.042 --> 00:44.502
Mmm, it's definitely
            a big whoop.

00:44.544 --> 00:46.046
Is he going to go
       to one of those prisons

00:46.087 --> 00:47.380
with tennis courts?

00:49.215 --> 00:52.260
I don't know, Susan.
    I suppose it's a possibility.

00:52.302 --> 00:55.680
I think we'll all be
            very relieved

00:55.722 --> 00:58.349
when the whole thing
            is behind us.

00:58.391 --> 01:01.061
--Pardon me.

01:01.102 --> 01:03.813
Mr. President,
     Mr. Rumsfeld and Mr. Cheney

01:03.855 --> 01:05.523
would like to speak
         with you urgently.

01:05.565 --> 01:07.442
-Thank you.
    -Thank you, sir.

01:17.285 --> 01:18.953
--Come on.

01:22.749 --> 01:26.002
I do not envy
       your father right now.

01:26.044 --> 01:28.588
You think Pat Nixon knew what
    was going on the whole time?

01:30.256 --> 01:32.258
-I don't know, honey.

01:32.300 --> 01:33.843
--I don't--

01:39.599 --> 01:42.685
I don't even know how much
        your dad can tell me.

01:44.104 --> 01:47.941
Who knows what
      President Nixon told Pat?

01:47.982 --> 01:50.068
Daddy is going to punish him,
              isn't he?

01:50.110 --> 01:53.029
Hmm. No, your father
      will do the right thing.

01:56.616 --> 01:59.828
History will write
           the true story

01:59.869 --> 02:01.496
of President Nixon.

02:01.538 --> 02:03.748
He has done good,
   but he's done irreparable harm

02:03.790 --> 02:06.918
in-- in standing up and lying,
            bold-facedly,

02:06.960 --> 02:08.878
to the people
        over and over again.

02:08.920 --> 02:11.214
It's, uh--
    It's a shattering experience

02:11.256 --> 02:14.467
to find a man in
   the highest office doing that.

02:16.136 --> 02:17.762
I, I, I

02:17.804 --> 02:19.556
I shot the sheriff

02:19.597 --> 02:22.308
Lord
       I didn't shot the deputy

02:22.350 --> 02:23.518
No

02:25.145 --> 02:27.230
Standing by, Mr. President.

02:27.272 --> 02:29.732
-   I... I...
        -   Shot the sheriff

02:29.774 --> 02:32.235
But I didn't shoot no deputy

02:36.531 --> 02:38.116
It's quite yellow.

02:38.158 --> 02:41.494
It's very cheerful.
       How's it going, Robert?

02:41.536 --> 02:43.329
It's going well.
          Thank you, ma'am.

02:44.330 --> 02:46.958
Oh, wow.
        Very floral, Mother.

02:47.000 --> 02:49.627
You are such a snob.

02:49.669 --> 02:52.297
-Huh, where do you get that?
   -Mr. Ford was asked

02:52.338 --> 02:55.216
by reporters what he would be
     doing for the rest of the day.

02:55.258 --> 02:57.719
He replied,
      "You will find out shortly."

02:57.760 --> 02:59.929
Three hours later,
       in his White House office,

02:59.971 --> 03:02.098
-this is what happened.
    -Mom, Daddy's on TV.

03:02.140 --> 03:04.976
Serious allegations
             and accusations

03:05.018 --> 03:09.105
hang like a sword over
      our former president's head.

03:09.147 --> 03:13.276
Finally, I feel that
 Richard Nixon and his loved ones

03:13.318 --> 03:15.445
have suffered enough

03:15.486 --> 03:19.199
and will continue to suffer,
          no matter what I do--

03:19.240 --> 03:23.119
no matter what we,
       as a great and good nation

03:23.161 --> 03:27.540
can do together to make
      his goal of peace come true.

03:30.251 --> 03:34.547
Now, therefore, I,
             Gerald R. Ford,

03:35.590 --> 03:38.051
president of the United States

03:39.510 --> 03:41.679
pursuant... 

03:41.721 --> 03:44.182
...to the pardon power
          conferred upon me

03:44.224 --> 03:47.894
by Article Two, Section Two
          of the Constitution,

03:47.936 --> 03:49.187
have granted,

03:49.229 --> 03:52.023
and by these presents, do grant

03:52.065 --> 03:56.653
a full, free and absolute pardon
         unto Richard Nixon

03:56.694 --> 03:59.614
for all offenses
        against the United States

03:59.656 --> 04:03.534
committed from January 20, 1969

04:03.576 --> 04:07.080
through August 9, 1974.

04:08.414 --> 04:10.458
We're off camera, Mr. President.

04:10.500 --> 04:12.543
pensive music

04:18.549 --> 04:20.843
There's been some angry reaction
        to the Nixon pardon.

04:20.885 --> 04:22.762
According to
         White House statistics,

04:22.804 --> 04:25.265
phone calls are heavy now,
          running about 50-50.

04:25.306 --> 04:27.016
But telegrams are six to one

04:27.058 --> 04:28.893
against
        the president's decision,

04:28.935 --> 04:30.895
600 to 700 telegrams an hour.

04:30.937 --> 04:32.772
One telegram from Virginia said,

04:32.814 --> 04:35.733
"Roosevelt had his New Deal.
        Truman had his Fair Deal.

04:35.775 --> 04:37.944
Now Ford has his crooked deal."

04:39.237 --> 04:40.446
Hi, there.

04:41.406 --> 04:42.782
What time is it?

04:45.576 --> 04:46.786
Why aren't you in bed?

04:53.710 --> 04:54.794
Everything all right?

04:58.214 --> 04:59.632
No, Jerry.

05:01.134 --> 05:02.427
It's not.

05:08.391 --> 05:11.102
Have you noticed
     that I never once asked you

05:11.144 --> 05:13.271
about those tapes?

05:15.940 --> 05:19.027
The burglaries, the wiretaps,

05:19.068 --> 05:21.696
who was involved,
        who wasn't involved.

05:21.738 --> 05:23.740
Anything about Watergate.

05:23.781 --> 05:25.658
I didn't know, Betty.

05:25.700 --> 05:28.411
Of course you didn't,
         because if you did,

05:28.453 --> 05:30.830
you wouldn't have been able
       to live with yourself.

05:31.956 --> 05:35.501
Do you realize how this
           makes you look?

05:37.879 --> 05:41.174
How this makes our family look?

05:44.135 --> 05:46.554
Hey, this was not
          an easy decision.

05:47.805 --> 05:50.600
I didn't go in there
      expecting to pardon him.

05:50.641 --> 05:52.268
Then why the fuck did you do it?

05:52.310 --> 05:54.437
To end the pain
         this country is in!

05:56.147 --> 05:59.400
I had my first press conference
     as president two days ago.

05:59.442 --> 06:01.819
The only thing any reporter,
       every last one of them,

06:01.861 --> 06:03.905
wanted to talk about was Nixon!

06:03.946 --> 06:05.740
Nothing about
        our economic crisis,

06:05.782 --> 06:08.242
nothing about our foreign policy
         issues. Just Nixon!

06:08.284 --> 06:09.577
So you let him off!

06:09.619 --> 06:11.496
He accepted the pardon!

06:13.373 --> 06:14.916
That is an admission of guilt!

06:14.957 --> 06:19.003
Without consequences
          for his actions!

06:23.841 --> 06:28.846
You know that this makes us
     look complicit, don't you?

06:28.888 --> 06:30.681
Like we're part of the cover-up!

06:39.190 --> 06:42.068
I know why I did
         what I did, Betty.

06:44.278 --> 06:46.656
If you don't believe in me,
        I can't change that.

06:46.697 --> 06:48.866
-No, you can't.

06:48.908 --> 06:50.868
I really believed
       you were going to bring

06:50.910 --> 06:53.746
some of your goodness
           to the office.

06:53.788 --> 06:56.332
dramatic music

07:24.610 --> 07:26.737
-Oh! I-- Sorry, ma'am.
           -Oh, pardon me.

07:40.168 --> 07:43.379
-Hi.
   -Can I help you?

07:43.421 --> 07:46.048
I'm here for Gerald Ford.

07:46.090 --> 07:47.633
Uh, down that way.

08:03.107 --> 08:07.487
Betty. How are ya?
      What are you doing here?

08:07.528 --> 08:09.405
Why haven't you told me?

08:12.158 --> 08:13.701
Do you wanna go outside
              and talk?

08:13.743 --> 08:16.037
Let's go outside and talk.

08:16.078 --> 08:17.955
-Let's go outside.
         -No, no, no. It's--

08:20.249 --> 08:22.627
It's because
        I'm a divorced woman.

08:24.086 --> 08:25.129
Yeah.

08:26.756 --> 08:28.633
I should've told you.
            Betty, hey--

08:28.674 --> 08:31.302
-Don't you touch me.
       -I should've told you.

08:31.344 --> 08:33.638
I'm sorry I made you feel like
      you weren't enough, okay?

08:33.679 --> 08:36.891
You are. You're enough,
      and I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

08:36.933 --> 08:38.809
It won't happen again.
            I messed up.

08:43.606 --> 08:45.149
No secrets.

08:46.817 --> 08:48.861
I won't.
      This won't happen again.

08:59.247 --> 09:01.290
This land is your land

09:03.834 --> 09:06.629
This land is my land

09:09.632 --> 09:12.134
From California

09:13.094 --> 09:17.181
To the New York island

09:17.974 --> 09:21.978
From the redwood forest

09:24.564 --> 09:27.858
To the Gulf Stream waters

09:28.651 --> 09:30.152
I tell you

09:30.194 --> 09:32.780
This land

09:32.822 --> 09:34.865
Was made for you and me

09:36.576 --> 09:37.743
Yeah

09:43.332 --> 09:47.378
One bright sunny morning

09:47.420 --> 09:51.257
In the shadow of the steeple

09:52.383 --> 09:57.179
Down by the welfare office

09:57.221 --> 10:01.726
I saw my people

10:01.767 --> 10:04.228
I was wondering

10:04.270 --> 10:07.189
If this land

10:07.231 --> 10:09.442
Was made for you and me

10:32.465 --> 10:35.092
Well, she was up
         early this morning

10:35.134 --> 10:36.761
doing all this cooking,
             and now...

10:36.802 --> 10:38.971
She said she would
       only be a few minutes.

10:39.013 --> 10:41.474
She in the room.
 We're sitting here ready to eat.

10:41.515 --> 10:42.808
Come on, now.

10:43.643 --> 10:45.603
Looks good, though.

10:45.645 --> 10:47.980
Marian! We're ready to eat.

10:48.022 --> 10:50.941
Go ahead.
          Start without me.

10:50.983 --> 10:54.028
Great, 'cause candied yams don't
   taste right when they're cold.

10:54.070 --> 10:56.364
Boy, don't try me on the eve
       of our Savior's birth.

10:56.405 --> 10:57.323
Put that spoon down.

10:58.949 --> 11:02.244
I'm on Craig's side
       about the candied yams.

11:02.286 --> 11:03.829
Let me see how long
           Mom's gonna be.

11:07.041 --> 11:11.879
My husband has MS.
      He needs his medication.

11:13.839 --> 11:17.176
Well, what's the point of
 insurance if you can't help him?

11:18.552 --> 11:22.848
We don't have $568!

11:25.142 --> 11:26.185
Well--

11:28.145 --> 11:29.188
Yeah.

11:31.399 --> 11:32.525
Thanks a lot.

11:38.030 --> 11:39.824
Merry fucking Christmas.

11:39.865 --> 11:41.575
melancholic music

12:06.016 --> 12:08.310
Oh, God, I would kill
      for some sugar right now.

12:08.352 --> 12:10.146
-Mel.
      -Proper chocolate.

12:10.187 --> 12:12.648
-Hey, Val.
             -Hey, Mich.

12:12.690 --> 12:14.233
How'd it go?

12:14.275 --> 12:16.152
Rahm won't consider
         any new legislation

12:16.193 --> 12:18.320
remotely connected
           to health care.

12:18.362 --> 12:20.156
He's obsessed with the Midterms.

12:20.197 --> 12:22.825
Uh-huh. I've been looking
   at those polls too, and yikes.

12:22.867 --> 12:24.201
Yeah, I'm worried.

12:24.243 --> 12:26.704
-Me too.
            -Barack loves

12:26.746 --> 12:29.582
the Healthy, Hunger-Free
       Kids Act, so fuck Rahm.

12:29.623 --> 12:31.667
-Just go do it. Get it started.

12:31.709 --> 12:35.045
I mean, who will not back a bill
      about children's health?

12:35.087 --> 12:36.505
Believe it or not,

12:36.547 --> 12:38.507
and I have this
       on the best authority,

12:38.549 --> 12:41.218
even Republicans have kids.

12:41.260 --> 12:42.928
-No.
                -Yes.

12:42.970 --> 12:44.597
I saw one once in the West Wing.

12:44.638 --> 12:46.390
Looked like a very tiny turtle.

12:46.432 --> 12:49.393
-Stop.

12:49.435 --> 12:51.604
You're so bad. I'm gonna
       tell 'em you said that.

12:51.645 --> 12:53.230
Oh, you absolutely--
          No, you are not!

12:53.272 --> 12:55.483
Don't say nothing till
      we pass that act, though.

12:55.524 --> 12:57.151
Don't you tell him what I said.

12:57.193 --> 12:58.736
-Shut the door.

12:58.778 --> 13:00.905
This is good news, ladies. So...

13:00.946 --> 13:03.407
The Healthy,
        Hunger-Free Kids Act.

13:03.449 --> 13:07.077
The goal is to fight childhood
      obesity and hunger together.

13:07.119 --> 13:09.705
This represents $4.5 billion

13:09.747 --> 13:11.248
of allocated funding

13:11.290 --> 13:12.875
which will then go
             to the schools.

13:27.014 --> 13:28.641
It's my happy place.

13:31.101 --> 13:33.729
This one?
    Get some hummus. Okay. Enjoy.

13:33.771 --> 13:35.940
Mrs. Obama,
    can we get a picture, please?

13:35.981 --> 13:37.733
Of course.

13:39.151 --> 13:41.153
-Thank you!
             -Thank you!

13:42.947 --> 13:45.407
I think we need some more
    extras. Do we have any more?

13:45.449 --> 13:48.035
Yeah, we'll just use these. That
    should be good enough, right?

13:49.537 --> 13:51.831
-Sylvie, which one do you want?
          -This one's fine.

13:51.872 --> 13:53.541
-Okay. Here you go.
        -Thank you.

13:53.582 --> 13:57.294
Sylvie.
     Did you want two of those?

13:59.588 --> 14:02.341
Oh, I'm sorry.
         I can put it back.

14:06.345 --> 14:08.973
The lunch ladies usually
       give me an extra lunch.

14:09.014 --> 14:10.474
This one's for my mom.

14:13.769 --> 14:17.857
Okay. You know what?
      Take this one too, okay?

14:24.321 --> 14:25.698
Take care of yourself.

14:25.739 --> 14:27.199
-I will.
               -Okay?

14:29.660 --> 14:31.954
-Mel! Okay.
            -Okay.

14:31.996 --> 14:35.207
-Senator Al Franken.
        -Oh, Senator Franken.

14:35.249 --> 14:37.042
-Yeah.
              -Uh-huh.

14:37.084 --> 14:39.211
-Senator Amy Klobuchar.
        -Amy will like this.

14:39.253 --> 14:40.880
She will love this.

14:42.172 --> 14:43.632
Yeah, you can take that one.

14:43.674 --> 14:46.051
And Senator Lindsey Graham.

14:46.093 --> 14:47.094
Hi.

14:48.345 --> 14:50.723
Give him extra eggplant.
             Or carrots.

14:50.764 --> 14:52.016
-These?
           -Love it.

14:52.057 --> 14:53.392
Let's hope there's no ethics law

14:53.434 --> 14:55.311
making veggies bribery.

14:56.145 --> 14:59.773
Hey, are you and Neil
             doing okay?

14:59.815 --> 15:01.066
Yeah, we're fine.

15:07.239 --> 15:10.034
-Actually, we're not fine.
                -Mmm.

15:10.075 --> 15:11.952
The other night,
    he told me that he feels like

15:11.994 --> 15:14.496
we're in an open marriage
         with my BlackBerry.

15:14.538 --> 15:16.916
Ooh. Susan...

15:18.167 --> 15:21.128
Listen, you know I appreciate
        the time you put in,

15:21.170 --> 15:23.631
but if you ever need to...

15:23.672 --> 15:25.299
Can I take the weekend?

15:25.341 --> 15:29.094
-Ladies, bad guy's here. Wow.
              -Oh, God.

15:30.554 --> 15:33.390
-What can I do for you, Rahm?
      -Very impressive.

15:33.432 --> 15:35.434
Um... Hi.

15:35.935 --> 15:39.355
We can't have you
 sending senators swag bags

15:39.396 --> 15:41.023
-from the White House garden.
              -Why not?

15:41.065 --> 15:43.192
Well, A, it makes us look
         fucking ridiculous.

15:43.233 --> 15:46.070
And B, because all of
    these brilliant conservatives

15:46.111 --> 15:47.863
somehow were able
       to convince the public

15:47.905 --> 15:50.366
that Obamacare equals
        government overreach

15:50.407 --> 15:52.701
and turning America
         into a nanny state.

15:52.743 --> 15:55.120
So now is not the time to say,

15:55.162 --> 15:57.665
"Hey, kids, why don't you
    swap out those cheeseburgers

15:57.706 --> 16:01.168
and have some kale
       and fucking cucumbers."

16:01.210 --> 16:02.544
Are you saying that Americans

16:02.586 --> 16:04.463
don't care
      about their kids' health?

16:05.381 --> 16:07.257
Type 2 diabetes, obesity,

16:07.299 --> 16:09.802
people living miles away
          from fresh food.

16:10.803 --> 16:12.972
Or do you not care about that?

16:13.514 --> 16:16.725
I don't want my kids eating
      that greasy shit either.

16:16.767 --> 16:18.936
But right now,
    we need to win the Midterms,

16:18.978 --> 16:21.355
and the Healthy,
        Hunger-Free Kids Act

16:21.397 --> 16:23.190
is not helping our poll numbers.

16:23.232 --> 16:26.860
If I were honest, I think
 that you have the wrong takeaway

16:26.902 --> 16:28.529
from these Midterm polls.

16:28.570 --> 16:30.698
Oh, really? Wow.

16:30.739 --> 16:32.533
Look, please,
      I'm begging you. Tell me.

16:32.574 --> 16:35.077
What is your expert political
         analysis on this--

16:35.119 --> 16:37.997
You didn't make health care
    personal. You didn't own it.

16:40.958 --> 16:43.460
I get that you're passionate
             about this,

16:43.502 --> 16:45.629
and I understand
       your connection to it.

16:45.671 --> 16:47.589
I know you don't think so,
              but I do.

16:47.631 --> 16:49.008
I'm telling you from experience.

16:49.049 --> 16:50.759
I learned the hard way,
             all right?

16:50.801 --> 16:52.803
Making things personal

16:52.845 --> 16:54.388
can get in the way
         of smart politics.

16:54.430 --> 16:56.557
Well, maybe sometimes
          you have to say,

16:56.598 --> 16:59.184
"Forget about smart politics,

16:59.226 --> 17:03.022
do what's right
        and trust the rest."

17:04.231 --> 17:06.066
That sounds amazing.

17:06.108 --> 17:07.568
But it's not realistic.

17:07.609 --> 17:09.820
You know what though?
          It's your realm.

17:09.862 --> 17:12.740
Do whatever you want. I'm just
     letting you know my opinion

17:12.781 --> 17:14.575
because I know
      you're dying to hear it.

17:14.616 --> 17:16.994
I think you're making a mistake.
             That's all.

17:17.036 --> 17:20.873
Sorry, please go back
         to your vegetation.

17:26.545 --> 17:29.339
gentle music

17:34.803 --> 17:36.430
Front page.

17:36.472 --> 17:39.349
Ooh! Oh, good.

17:39.767 --> 17:42.227
Definitely not a puff piece.

17:42.269 --> 17:44.938
Hmm. Thank you, Samuel.

17:46.190 --> 17:47.232
Thank you.

17:51.195 --> 17:52.488
Morning, Louis.

17:52.529 --> 17:53.989
-Morning.
               -Louis.

17:54.031 --> 17:54.990
Tommy.

17:56.116 --> 17:57.242
That's some article.

17:57.284 --> 18:00.287
Oh, I haven't read it.

18:00.329 --> 18:01.747
Everyone else has.

18:03.332 --> 18:04.750
-Oh?
          -Usually,

18:04.792 --> 18:06.585
one consults with the president

18:06.627 --> 18:08.462
before giving direct quotes
            to reporters

18:08.504 --> 18:10.255
announcing cuts
      to White House spending.

18:10.297 --> 18:12.341
Oh, nothing stopped him
           from saying it.

18:12.382 --> 18:14.635
Yeah.
     Actually, many things did.

18:14.676 --> 18:17.846
Uh, let's see.
         Tact, um, strategy,

18:17.888 --> 18:20.808
timing, a desire
      for a positive outcome...

18:20.849 --> 18:22.893
I believe that an administration

18:22.935 --> 18:25.813
demonstrating fiscal austerity
         during a depression

18:25.854 --> 18:28.148
can most certainly lead
       to a positive outcome.

18:28.190 --> 18:31.151
Right. Um, Eleanor, there is
 a way that things are done here.

18:31.193 --> 18:33.821
You know,
      a great political adviser

18:33.862 --> 18:37.199
once told me to stop laughing

18:37.241 --> 18:39.159
when I spoke of serious things.

18:39.201 --> 18:41.036
That adviser,

18:41.078 --> 18:44.998
the same adviser who became one
     of my most trusted friends,

18:45.040 --> 18:47.876
also told me that I should
     lower the pitch of my voice

18:47.918 --> 18:50.921
so that men would not dismiss me
        as a frivolous woman.

18:50.963 --> 18:54.007
Now everyone,
       including that friend,

18:54.049 --> 18:56.051
is telling me to be quiet.

18:56.093 --> 18:58.387
This is the highest office
            in the land.

18:58.428 --> 19:01.348
You have a wide audience
            to win over.

19:01.390 --> 19:05.018
Being contrary doesn't translate
       into widespread appeal.

19:05.060 --> 19:09.648
I see. People prefer pleasant.

19:09.690 --> 19:12.818
The president's advisers
       think his goddamn wife

19:12.860 --> 19:14.987
should stay in the background!

19:15.028 --> 19:18.323
Hick's article is positive,
       yes, but the others...

19:18.365 --> 19:19.408
Well...

19:21.034 --> 19:24.079
they seem to have asked
    their cartoonist to be as...

19:25.247 --> 19:26.498
cruel as possible.

19:30.919 --> 19:31.962
Louis.

19:33.338 --> 19:37.426
Not everyone likes you
          as much as we do.

19:37.467 --> 19:39.344
pensive music

19:46.351 --> 19:48.103
I know ten female reporters

19:48.145 --> 19:50.147
who've been let go
    now that the election's over.

19:50.189 --> 19:52.316
-No.
             -Yes. Yes.

19:54.026 --> 19:55.986
Is your job secure?

19:56.028 --> 19:57.070
Yeah.

19:59.031 --> 20:00.616
Thanks to our collaboration,

20:00.657 --> 20:02.993
the AP offered me
     White House Correspondent,

20:03.035 --> 20:05.370
exclusively covering you.

20:05.412 --> 20:06.580
No.

20:07.831 --> 20:11.877
What, a whole job
    just dedicated to one person?

20:11.919 --> 20:13.629
That seems a bit excessive.

20:13.670 --> 20:15.505
-Doesn't it?
        -No. That's nonsense.

20:15.547 --> 20:17.883
You already helped appoint
 the first female cabinet member.

20:17.925 --> 20:20.552
I know you gave the president
        a long list of women.

20:20.594 --> 20:23.222
I did, but Frances Perkins
            wasn't on it.

20:23.263 --> 20:27.643
Well, still,
    it's an historic appointment.

20:27.684 --> 20:29.519
You put the issue
          front and center.

20:29.561 --> 20:30.729
I suppose.

20:30.771 --> 20:32.898
I can't wait to see what's next.

20:32.940 --> 20:36.902
Well, I'm afraid
   you'll be sorely disappointed.

20:36.944 --> 20:40.197
I'm a bit unseasoned
            for politics.

20:40.239 --> 20:43.325
And clearly too ugly
           for First Lady.

20:44.910 --> 20:46.245
This guy...

20:46.787 --> 20:49.581
This guy is an ignorant,
           talentless hack

20:49.623 --> 20:51.041
who isn't fit
        to shine your shoes.

20:51.083 --> 20:54.461
If you can't see
      how beautiful you are...

20:54.503 --> 20:58.131
You have an audience,
   your radio show, your columns,

20:58.173 --> 21:02.427
and the most powerful man
       in the country. Use it.

21:10.769 --> 21:12.354
"One's philosophy

21:12.396 --> 21:16.066
is not best expressed in words.

21:16.108 --> 21:20.028
It is expressed
      in the choices one makes.

21:20.070 --> 21:21.738
And the choices we make

21:21.780 --> 21:25.450
are ultimately
         our responsibility.

21:25.492 --> 21:29.913
Do what you feel
     in your heart to be right,

21:29.955 --> 21:34.042
for you'll be criticized anyway.

21:34.084 --> 21:38.463
No matter how plain
           a woman may be,

21:38.505 --> 21:41.133
if truth and honesty

21:41.174 --> 21:43.969
are written across her face,

21:44.011 --> 21:47.139
she will be beautiful."

21:53.270 --> 21:55.856
A female-only press conference?

21:55.897 --> 21:58.525
Yes. Led by Mrs. Roosevelt.

21:58.567 --> 22:00.610
Well, Franklin is so busy now,

22:00.652 --> 22:02.863
and it will allow me to share

22:02.904 --> 22:05.073
in the very important
            and good work

22:05.115 --> 22:07.034
this administration is doing.

22:07.075 --> 22:10.120
Yes, and it would promote
      the employment of women.

22:14.791 --> 22:18.628
As press secretary, all events
    in this house go through me.

22:18.670 --> 22:21.131
And this idea reveals

22:21.173 --> 22:24.760
is a misunderstanding,
   a clear, basic misunderstanding

22:24.801 --> 22:28.096
of your role in this house.

22:28.138 --> 22:29.931
The role of First Lady

22:29.973 --> 22:33.018
has never officially
      been defined or codified.

22:33.060 --> 22:37.314
But the expectations have,
        by time and practice.

22:37.356 --> 22:40.025
-I cannot allow this.
         -"Allow"?

22:41.985 --> 22:45.697
Mr. Early,
 this conversation is a courtesy.

22:48.075 --> 22:50.827
Steve, this is clearly
       a good idea, all right?

22:50.869 --> 22:54.122
It enables communication
       between the White House

22:54.164 --> 22:56.750
and American women--
      a voter base, by the way.

22:56.792 --> 22:59.252
A base that will grow and grow.

22:59.294 --> 23:01.630
A growing voter base
     that we will very much need

23:01.671 --> 23:04.174
by our side in
     the next election, clearly.

23:07.719 --> 23:10.180
I can't approve this agenda.
         It's too political.

23:10.222 --> 23:12.974
What is there
        other than politics?

23:13.016 --> 23:14.768
Women's issues.

23:14.810 --> 23:18.355
Cooking and cleaning
            and sewing--

23:18.397 --> 23:21.858
You would like me
     to hold a press conference

23:21.900 --> 23:24.027
to discuss dusting?

23:24.069 --> 23:25.529
Or baking.

23:25.570 --> 23:26.863
Vacuuming?

23:26.905 --> 23:28.073
Knitting.

23:32.119 --> 23:35.497
Yes, these are all great.
        These are all great.

23:35.539 --> 23:39.793
--Goodbye, Mr. Early. Thank you.

23:43.797 --> 23:46.800
Remind me never
          to ask him again.

23:53.765 --> 23:58.812
Were you aware that Joe Namath
    has a gentle, sensitive side?

23:58.854 --> 24:01.857
-Look how gentle he looks.
         -So gentle.

24:01.898 --> 24:04.943
-Very gentle.

24:06.361 --> 24:10.031
It's just nice to read about
   something other than Watergate.

24:10.073 --> 24:13.535
Oh, speaking of, your new
 press secretary starts tomorrow.

24:13.577 --> 24:15.078
We need to get a meeting
            in the books.

24:15.120 --> 24:17.414
-Hello, Mrs. Howe.

24:17.456 --> 24:18.874
Oh, Madam First Lady.

24:18.915 --> 24:20.542
Oh, good afternoon.

24:20.584 --> 24:21.835
She's my moral support.

24:21.877 --> 24:23.712
I see. Ready for your mammogram?

24:23.753 --> 24:25.255
Ready as I'll ever be!

24:25.297 --> 24:27.382
I'll be in
     the waiting room with Joe.

24:27.424 --> 24:30.886
Wait, Betty... You've never had
       a mammogram, have you?

24:30.927 --> 24:31.803
No.

24:33.013 --> 24:35.098
Can you make room
     for the First Lady, Doctor?

24:35.140 --> 24:37.893
-Nancy.
     -Well, everyone's supposed

24:37.934 --> 24:39.895
to have a mammogram.
        Right, Dr. Goldberg?

24:39.936 --> 24:42.397
We suggest women over 50
    be screened every year, yes.

24:42.439 --> 24:44.232
See? And they don't tell us
             this stuff.

24:44.274 --> 24:46.735
Another way that women
        are kept in the dark.

24:46.776 --> 24:48.570
We'd be happy to fit you in
           if you'd like.

24:48.612 --> 24:50.572
Then I don't have
          to suffer alone.

24:50.614 --> 24:52.908
It's not that bad.
   A little uncomfortable at most.

24:52.949 --> 24:56.244
Basically like laying down
       on a cold garage floor

24:56.286 --> 24:58.121
and pulling out your breast
         and having someone

24:58.163 --> 24:59.748
-run over it with a car.
               -Nice.

24:59.789 --> 25:01.708
I'm kidding. Kind of.

25:01.750 --> 25:04.044
It's just a little pressure.
     Be over before you know it.

25:04.085 --> 25:05.921
You're doing it.
     Mammogram for two, please.

25:05.962 --> 25:07.339
Nurse will bring in your robes.

25:07.923 --> 25:12.427
I'm really not sure
     if I wanna do this, Nancy.

25:12.469 --> 25:14.930
It's a little uncomfortable,
    but it'll be quick and easy.

25:14.971 --> 25:17.474
And you're my friend and I want
    you here as long as possible.

25:17.516 --> 25:18.558
-Okay?
               -Okay.

25:18.600 --> 25:19.768
-For me.
               -Okay.

25:22.145 --> 25:23.939
-Mrs. Ford.
         -Thank you.

25:23.980 --> 25:25.565
-Of course.
                -Wow.

25:25.607 --> 25:28.109
-Yeah.
         -That's efficient.

25:28.151 --> 25:30.195
pensive music

25:35.158 --> 25:38.537
Mrs. Ford. Thank you
   for giving us a bit more time.

25:38.578 --> 25:40.997
This is Dr. Fouty,
          Chief of Surgery.

25:41.039 --> 25:42.707
He'd like to examine
         you a bit further,

25:42.749 --> 25:45.335
-if that's all right with you.
           -Oh, of course.

25:45.377 --> 25:47.379
Just lie back on the table,
             Mrs. Ford.

25:51.091 --> 25:53.218
-Promise I will make this quick.
            -Mmm.

25:56.012 --> 25:57.347
Just right here.

25:58.765 --> 26:01.643
-Is there a problem?
       -Just extra precaution.

26:01.685 --> 26:03.311
We're double checking.

26:13.321 --> 26:14.406
Okay.

26:16.658 --> 26:18.743
-Any pain here?
              -Mm-mmm.

26:19.828 --> 26:20.870
Mm-hmm.

26:24.249 --> 26:25.834
Very good. Okay.

26:25.875 --> 26:27.961
You can get dressed.

26:28.003 --> 26:30.213
Mmm. Thank you.

26:30.255 --> 26:32.716
-That's it?
             -That's it.

26:34.092 --> 26:36.469
I will contact you
    if we need to see you again.

26:36.511 --> 26:37.596
Thank you.

26:38.555 --> 26:40.015
Thank you, Mrs. Ford.

26:57.032 --> 26:59.951
pensive music

27:04.831 --> 27:06.791
-Susan.
                -Mom.

27:06.833 --> 27:09.294
What is it? Oh.

27:10.587 --> 27:12.380
-Dr. Lushkin.
            -Dr. Lushkin.

27:12.422 --> 27:16.009
I-- I'm terribly sorry.
        Um, uh, Susan came in

27:16.051 --> 27:18.845
-and-- and we were discussing--
   -I needed something for my cold

27:18.887 --> 27:20.221
and so I went to see
            Dr. Lushkin,

27:20.263 --> 27:22.015
and he asked where you were,

27:22.057 --> 27:23.850
that he needed to talk
       to you about something

27:23.892 --> 27:25.310
and I made him tell me why.

27:27.771 --> 27:32.233
Uh, Betty. Your, um, mammogram
        and examination today

27:32.275 --> 27:34.277
revealed a tumor.

27:34.319 --> 27:35.487
Hmm.

27:39.115 --> 27:40.867
Tumors can be removed, right?

27:40.909 --> 27:43.370
Uh, Dr. Fouty
      would like to do a biopsy

27:43.411 --> 27:44.829
as quickly as possible.

27:46.122 --> 27:48.875
To see if the tumor
          is... cancerous.

27:50.001 --> 27:52.962
Correct.
    Depending on size and spread,

27:53.004 --> 27:55.757
we may recommend undergoing
        a mastectomy, ma'am.

27:56.883 --> 27:57.967
I see.

27:58.968 --> 28:00.845
What exactly is that?

28:00.887 --> 28:05.266
It's a partial, and sometimes
    full, removal of the breast.

28:07.560 --> 28:10.522
I'd like to schedule something
            for tomorrow.

28:10.563 --> 28:12.273
Oh, no. I can't.

28:12.315 --> 28:14.901
-Tomorrow I have a full day.
       -Mom, are you kidding?

28:14.943 --> 28:16.695
Is it safe for her
          to wait 24 hours?

28:16.736 --> 28:18.446
Well, no longer than that.

28:19.531 --> 28:21.658
That's what we'll do then.

28:21.700 --> 28:24.327
-Thank you, Dr. Lushkin.
         -Thank you, Doctor.

28:41.344 --> 28:45.223
"Yesterday,
       I accompanied a friend

28:46.391 --> 28:48.059
to the doctor.

28:49.144 --> 28:52.021
Um, she was getting a mammogram.

28:52.063 --> 28:55.233
For support, I got one too.

28:55.275 --> 28:59.779
Unfortunately,
         the results of mine

28:59.821 --> 29:04.451
showed some... abnormalities."

29:04.492 --> 29:08.747
May I suggest something
      more along the lines of,

29:08.788 --> 29:10.999
"I went in
      for a routine procedure.

29:11.040 --> 29:14.169
-Everything came back clean."
    -That doesn't make any sense.

29:14.210 --> 29:16.004
But if they do find cancer,

29:16.045 --> 29:19.007
saying something came back clean
      when it didn't is lying.

29:19.048 --> 29:20.675
I'm an expert at finessing.

